+You are editing this local Survivor.io optimizer repo. You may edit code, but be conservative and test everything. Do not reorganize folders. Do not delete source data. Do not run long training. Do not weaken quality, coverage, audits, or false-prune safety. Keep CUDA single-owner rule: shared ranker is the only CUDA owner; CPU workers must not touch CUDA.
+
+Current clean baseline: 3-min proof passed with 3300 profiles, 15.8 profiles/sec, 15/15 systems covered, learned usage 100%, false_prune_rate 0, preprune_false_prune_rate 0. Problem: GPU idle ~82.8%, reason waiting_for_cpu_candidates. Main bottleneck: CPU candidate generation/search is starving RTX 4070.
+
+Long-term goal: make the optimizer faster and smarter over time, use GPU more, safely learn from runs, compact old learning memory, and eventually power a full Survivor.io web calculator with explainable DPS-first recommendations.
+
+Do this in safe stages.
+
+Stage 1: Add a hotspot profiler, not a big rewrite. Create or improve tools/profile_training_hotspots.py. It should run a small sample and report global planner time, action generation time, candidate row creation time, duplicate candidate count, state copy/rebuild count, GPU queue fill/wait, per-system candidate counts, and top likely waste areas. Command should be:
+python tools/profile_training_hotspots.py --profiles 100 --device cuda
+
+Stage 2: Improve metrics. Add stable metrics for CPU candidate seconds, global planner seconds, state_copy_count, state_rebuild_count, candidate_count_before_dedupe, candidate_count_after_dedupe, duplicate_candidates_removed, average_gpu_batch_size, gpu_queue_fill_rate, learned_candidates_reordered, learned_candidates_removed, learned_candidates_saved, and systems_covered_count. Do not hardcode fake metrics.
+
+Stage 3: Small safe performance improvement only. Focus on deduping equivalent candidates before expensive state transitions and reducing repeated state copy/rebuild work. Prefer caching static profile features, breakpoint/effect evals, and action/effect keys. Do not lower BeamSize, ChainDepth, MaxActionsPerProfile, audits, exploration, or systems.
+
+Stage 4: Add learning memory maintenance tools:
+python tools/maintain_learning_memory.py --dry-run
+python tools/maintain_learning_memory.py --apply
+Dry-run must show current sizes, stale/duplicate/low-confidence buckets, bad old priors, estimated size reduction, and what is kept/removed. Apply must backup first. Never delete source truth, human knowledge, audit failures, latest checkpoint, or high-value examples. Only compact/merge/retire generated learning artifacts.
+
+Stage 5: Add tests. Tests must prove: no CUDA ownership regression, all 15 observable systems remain covered in small proof when possible, false prune rates stay 0, memory dry-run never deletes source truth, apply creates backup, stale bad priors can retire, compaction keeps audit/failure examples, and new metrics are real.
+
+Verification allowed: targeted pytest, profiler with small profile count, one 1-min smoke if needed, one final 3-min proof. No overnight run. Final proof must compare to baseline: 15.8 profiles/sec, GPU idle 82.8%, batch utilization 38.8%, learned usage 100%, systems 15/15, false prunes 0.
+
+Report back with changed files, tests run, profiler output, final 3-min metrics, and exact next command.
+

